WEBVTT

00:01.380 --> 00:08.460
Welcome to Wait, I Qualify, the show about unlocking aid for real people right here in Nevada County. I'm Shawna.

00:08.940 --> 00:22.020
And I'm Jeff, Shawna's twin. We're from techandpower.org, a local nonprofit dedicated to helping folks find the help and incentives they're entitled to, from the state, the federal government, and local organizations.

00:22.500 --> 00:30.880
This is our very first episode, so we're starting with the big one. Today we're busting the four myths that stop people from ever applying for help in the first place.

00:31.480 --> 00:37.500
Because here's the secret of this whole show, most people qualify for more than they think, and most of that help goes unclaimed.

00:38.840 --> 00:41.880
A lot more than they think. Let's get into it.

00:42.600 --> 00:49.740
So, Jeff, aren't these kind of benefits just for the truly destitute, for folks with no money or experiencing homelessness?

00:49.740 --> 00:58.080
No, and honestly, Shawna, that's the single biggest myth out there. People hear low income and assume it means almost nothing.

00:58.560 --> 01:07.900
Here's the truth. The official poverty line for a family of four this year is $33,000, and many assistance programs consider you low income at up to double that.

01:08.320 --> 01:11.540
$66,000 a year for a family of four.

01:12.020 --> 01:17.500
$66,000 a year. That's a lot more than most people think of when they think of low income.

01:17.500 --> 01:26.040
And for housing help, it goes even higher. The federal housing agency, it's called HUD, draws its own line, county by county.

01:26.460 --> 01:32.300
Here in Nevada County, their official low income is just over $100,000 a year for a family of four.

01:33.140 --> 01:38.880
So a household making $100,000 here in Nevada County can count as low income for housing programs?

01:38.880 --> 01:45.920
That's right. And some programs go higher still. There's even help for first time home buyers.

01:46.540 --> 01:51.400
But we'll get to specific programs all season long. For today, just hold on to this.

01:51.740 --> 01:56.340
Every program draws its own line, and almost every line is higher than people guess.

01:57.660 --> 02:03.140
So for getting benefits from the government, the answer to doing make too much is?

02:03.700 --> 02:07.860
Don't guess. Check. And that's actually the point of this show.

02:09.360 --> 02:13.860
So why do you think these income lines are so much higher than most people expect them to be?

02:14.760 --> 02:20.980
It's because the math of everyday life changed. In recent years, the paychecks have mostly kept up with everyday prices.

02:21.260 --> 02:30.420
But the essentials have not played fair. Housing, healthcare, childcare, the things you can't skip, have grown far faster than wages.

02:30.420 --> 02:38.260
And the long run picture is worse. Since the last 70s, the American economy became about 87%.

02:38.260 --> 02:48.380
Since the late 70s, the American economy became about 87% more productive. The typical workers pay grew only about 33%.

02:48.380 --> 02:57.600
Yeah, I feel like a lot of people are experiencing that right now, where it feels like even just buying food or gas or things like that just feels way tighter than it used to.

02:57.600 --> 03:03.580
So even though the country got richer, people's paychecks didn't seem to reflect that.

03:04.420 --> 03:13.500
And housing is the worst of it. Look at this chart. A typical home recently hit a record selling for more than five times what a typical household earns in a year.

03:14.100 --> 03:16.460
25 years ago, three times as normal.

03:17.600 --> 03:25.300
And many people in our generation can't even own a home right now. So people working full time are finding that the math just doesn't work out.

03:25.900 --> 03:32.000
Exactly. And that is exactly who these programs are for. Not other people. You.

03:34.020 --> 03:46.140
Okay, myth number two, and I hear this from a lot of different people, including when I worked at the VA, veterans were constantly not wanting to apply for benefits because they felt like there were people that deserved it more than them.

03:46.280 --> 03:52.060
So people think if I sign up, aren't I taking benefits from someone else who deserves it more or needs it more?

03:53.760 --> 04:02.180
Yeah, this myth is the one I want to bust the most because it stops generous, conscientious people from getting help they've earned.

04:02.600 --> 04:08.980
The answer is no. And here's why. Let's name the big programs because we'll be talking about them all season.

04:09.840 --> 04:16.560
CalFresh. That's California's grocery money. What people folks used to call, they used to call food stamps.

04:17.360 --> 04:26.160
Medi-Cal. That's free or low cost health coverage. The earned income tax credit. Extra cash back at the tax time for people who work.

04:26.560 --> 04:33.320
And SSI, monthly checks for seniors and people with disabilities living on very little. Here's the thing about all four.

04:33.820 --> 04:39.220
There is no fixed pot of money. The law says if you qualify, the help is yours by right.

04:39.220 --> 04:46.300
And the funding grows to cover every eligible person who signs up. Your benefits do not come out of your neighbor's pocket.

04:46.500 --> 04:48.400
That's literally how the law is written.

04:49.100 --> 04:52.780
So there's not a line that I'm cutting in and forcing someone else out of?

04:54.180 --> 04:58.180
For the big programs, no line at all. And here's the part that gets me.

04:58.660 --> 05:07.360
Every year, an estimated $60 billion or more benefits go unclaimed across this country because eligible people never apply.

05:07.360 --> 05:10.040
$60 billion. That's a lot.

05:10.840 --> 05:18.140
Every year, right here in California, about one in five people who qualify for CalFresh grocery help aren't getting it.

05:18.300 --> 05:22.700
And about one in five workers who've earned the tax time cash back, they never claim it.

05:23.740 --> 05:28.620
That's money that has been allocated for people already that's just sitting there on the table.

05:29.620 --> 05:30.980
That's right. Left on the table.

05:31.700 --> 05:35.540
Now, one honest exception, because we'll always be straight with you on the show.

05:35.900 --> 05:39.260
A few programs do have limited funding and waiting lists.

05:39.640 --> 05:43.720
The big example is Section 8, the federal program that helps you pay your monthly rent.

05:44.280 --> 05:48.080
But even there, applying doesn't take help away from anyone who already has it.

05:48.520 --> 05:52.720
It just gets you in a line. And if you never apply, you're not in a line at all.

05:53.540 --> 06:00.200
One more thing. If a program accepts you as eligible, that means you fit the exact group that the program is built to serve.

06:00.200 --> 06:06.860
These eligibility rules are strict. If you pass them, you're not shooting the system. You are who the help is for.

06:08.960 --> 06:12.620
Here's another myth people don't say out loud usually, but everyone feels.

06:13.060 --> 06:18.500
Why would I deserve free or reduced-price things? Is an accepting handout somehow bad?

06:19.780 --> 06:24.080
Let me reframe that. The help you get from these programs is a tiny drop in the bucket

06:24.080 --> 06:29.600
compared to the help and money that wealthy organizations and people receive from the government every single year.

06:29.600 --> 06:36.860
If you think quote-unquote good people or wealthy people don't take government support, you're flat out wrong.

06:37.460 --> 06:38.800
Let me give you three examples.

06:39.380 --> 06:48.060
Example 1. Big corporations. Researchers tracked hundreds of big corporations that stayed profitable every single year for five straight years.

06:48.720 --> 06:54.460
On average, they paid about 14% in federal income tax. Not the 21% that the law says.

06:55.280 --> 06:58.740
About one in three of them paid zero at least one of those years.

06:58.740 --> 07:00.980
And a few did even better than zero.

07:02.080 --> 07:05.680
Better than zero? Like they paid less than zero in taxes? What does that mean?

07:06.320 --> 07:13.520
Yes, that's exactly right. 23 of them over all five years combined paid nothing at all or even less.

07:14.140 --> 07:22.520
Some literally got money back. All of it perfectly legal. Tax breaks for buying equipment, for how they pay their executives, for doing research.

07:22.880 --> 07:27.020
And Congress made those breaks bigger and permanent just last year.

07:27.020 --> 07:33.440
So a billion-dollar company feels totally fine paying zero dollars in taxes,

07:33.440 --> 07:39.440
but a working family will often feel guilty about just getting a couple hundred dollars in help for their food bill.

07:40.320 --> 07:48.520
That's the absurdity. Yes, example 2. Bailouts. When big industries hit a crisis, the government steps in every time.

07:49.000 --> 07:55.120
In 2008, Congress put up $700 billion in emergency rescue money for the banks.

07:55.120 --> 08:00.900
And out of the same pot, the carmakers, GM and Chrysler, got tens of billions too.

08:01.820 --> 08:05.840
And that wasn't just a one-time thing. That's a way the system is designed.

08:06.860 --> 08:11.020
Yeah, it wasn't one time, not even close. When the pandemic grounded air travel,

08:11.320 --> 08:17.100
passenger airlines got about $54 billion to keep paying their workers.

08:17.560 --> 08:21.600
And in 2023, when a big bank called Silicon Valley Bank collapsed,

08:21.600 --> 08:28.440
the government stepped in so every person and business with money...

08:30.360 --> 08:34.700
And in 2023, when a big bank called Silicon Valley Bank collapsed,

08:34.920 --> 08:40.000
the government stepped in so every person and business with money in the bank got every dollar back.

08:40.520 --> 08:43.040
Even amounts way above that. Look up.

08:44.920 --> 08:48.420
Even amounts way above what the government normally protects.

08:48.420 --> 08:51.280
Nobody called those CEOs freeloaders.

08:52.500 --> 08:58.440
So wild. So why is it fine? Why do corporations feel perfectly fine getting big bailouts

08:59.120 --> 09:02.400
or money from the government when they hit a roadblock or just aren't doing well?

09:03.040 --> 09:08.680
But individual people feel like they shouldn't get a little bit of help when the same thing happens to them.

09:09.580 --> 09:13.380
That's exactly the right question. And nobody has ever given me a good answer.

09:14.100 --> 09:15.800
So let's bring it even closer to home.

09:15.800 --> 09:18.880
Example three. And this one's about your coworkers.

09:19.640 --> 09:25.600
Back in 2020, a government watchdog agency studied who was actually receiving food assistance and Medicaid.

09:27.100 --> 09:30.820
Medicaid is the national name for what we call Medi-Cal here in California.

09:31.460 --> 09:37.040
In every state, they looked at the top employers of people on those benefits were household names.

09:37.620 --> 09:41.080
Walmart was number one. McDonald's usually right behind.

09:41.420 --> 09:44.540
And about seven in 10 of those folks were working full time.

09:44.540 --> 09:51.080
Wages have come up since then. Walmart says its average store worker now makes about $18.25 an hour.

09:52.340 --> 09:55.560
So these big corporations that we've heard of, Walmart, McDonald's,

09:56.300 --> 10:01.680
they're paying their employees less than employees need just to get the basics in their life

10:01.680 --> 10:04.380
so that they can make a profit.

10:05.320 --> 10:10.520
And here in Nevada County, covering the basics for just one adult takes over $27 an hour,

10:10.520 --> 10:13.520
which is a lot more than the amount you mentioned.

10:13.520 --> 10:16.140
Way more. That's exactly right.

10:16.520 --> 10:21.980
So working a full time job at a big name employer and still qualifying for help isn't a personal failure.

10:22.280 --> 10:24.520
It's the system working exactly as designed.

10:25.240 --> 10:30.020
So when someone skips getting the benefits they're eligible for out of pride...

10:30.020 --> 10:32.740
They're giving up a tiny bit of money on principle.

10:33.180 --> 10:39.780
While the wealthiest 1% who hold roughly a third of all the wealth in this country take everything they can with zero shame.

10:39.780 --> 10:43.840
If you want the full story, there's a brand new book about exactly this.

10:44.400 --> 10:48.860
It's called Escape from Capitalism by the economist Clara Mattai.

10:49.220 --> 10:55.540
Her point is simple. When benefits for working people get cut, there's a political choice, not a law of nature.

10:56.480 --> 10:59.120
So take what you've earned, the wealthy already do.

11:00.980 --> 11:03.220
Last myth. This is a quiet one.

11:03.500 --> 11:07.200
A lot of people think it's scary to hand all my personal information to the government.

11:07.200 --> 11:11.580
And what if I'm applying and I do something wrong and I get punished somehow?

11:12.040 --> 11:14.760
A lot of people don't apply out of the fear of that happening.

11:15.260 --> 11:20.120
That's true. And the fear is real. I want to honor it, then take it apart.

11:20.920 --> 11:27.100
First the good news. Most benefit programs have strict privacy and security rules written into federal law.

11:27.520 --> 11:30.760
Your information is only supposed to be used to run the program itself.

11:31.900 --> 11:34.820
Now the honest part, because we promise to be straight with you.

11:34.820 --> 11:38.760
The current federal administration has rolled some of that back.

11:39.360 --> 11:40.560
And people should know about it.

11:41.020 --> 11:47.280
In 2025, ICE, the Immigration Enforcement Agency, was given access to Medicaid's records.

11:47.940 --> 11:55.460
The list of everyone signed up, that's about 79 million people all over the country.

11:56.220 --> 11:58.920
California and 21 other states sued.

11:59.500 --> 12:03.900
Right now for Californians, a court order says only basic information can be shared.

12:03.900 --> 12:08.320
No medical records, and only about people who aren't there lawfully.

12:09.180 --> 12:10.680
That fight is still in court.

12:11.820 --> 12:15.960
So what does that mean practically for people that might be thinking of applying for these benefits?

12:17.100 --> 12:20.000
For most people, applying is still safe. Full stop.

12:21.040 --> 12:24.400
But if anyone in your household isn't a citizen, do one thing first.

12:24.760 --> 12:28.040
Get free advice from a legal aid or immigration non-profit.

12:28.040 --> 12:29.180
And know this.

12:29.640 --> 12:34.060
Immigration officials use something called the public charge rule when they decide green cards.

12:34.660 --> 12:41.220
Under that rule, as it stands today, using food health coverage or housing assistance does not count against you.

12:42.060 --> 12:44.460
Okay, and what about the what if I do it wrong fear?

12:45.980 --> 12:46.720
Here's the truth.

12:47.020 --> 12:51.320
If you apply honestly and it turns out you don't qualify, nothing bad happens.

12:51.800 --> 12:52.040
Nothing.

12:52.740 --> 12:54.080
The worst outcome is a no.

12:54.520 --> 12:56.480
There's no penalty for being told no.

12:56.480 --> 12:58.820
Just two things to keep in mind.

12:59.300 --> 13:00.840
One, always answer truthfully.

13:01.300 --> 13:02.160
Being wrong is fine.

13:02.760 --> 13:04.040
Honest mistakes are not fraud.

13:04.860 --> 13:08.200
Knowingly giving false information is the one thing that does carry penalties.

13:09.220 --> 13:17.040
Two, if a program ever overpays you by mistake, even their mistake, you can ask for that money back later.

13:17.860 --> 13:21.680
So when your income changes, report it promptly and never be surprised.

13:22.040 --> 13:24.100
They can ask for that money back later, right?

13:24.100 --> 13:28.560
So if they accidentally overpay you, they might then require you to pay them back.

13:29.760 --> 13:29.900
Yeah.

13:30.580 --> 13:34.860
Well, and what if someone applies and then changes their mind?

13:35.980 --> 13:39.640
You can take back your application at any time before there's a decision.

13:40.020 --> 13:42.480
No penalty and apply again later whenever you want.

13:42.960 --> 13:46.080
If you're already enrolled, you can ask to close your case at any time.

13:46.480 --> 13:48.680
You're in control of this process the whole way through.

13:49.720 --> 13:52.000
Look, it's scary to do anything new.

13:52.000 --> 13:57.900
But in this kind of scary, it's the kind that might actually end with money in your pocket and food on your table.

13:59.480 --> 14:01.360
So let's recap the four myths.

14:02.100 --> 14:05.440
So the first one, benefits aren't just for the destitute.

14:05.660 --> 14:10.480
A family of four here can make $66,000, sometimes over $100,000, and still qualify.

14:11.260 --> 14:12.900
You're not taking anything from anyone.

14:13.500 --> 14:19.640
For the big programs, the funding grows when you enroll and $60 billion a year goes completely unclaimed.

14:20.760 --> 14:22.480
Good people don't take help.

14:22.880 --> 14:27.600
Tell that to the corporations, the banks, and the airlines that are constantly getting help from the government.

14:28.380 --> 14:32.440
And if you apply honestly, the worst thing that can happen is somebody tells you no.

14:33.560 --> 14:35.900
Corey, we go. Write these down.

14:35.980 --> 14:38.800
If you remember nothing else from today, these resources are very helpful.

14:39.280 --> 14:41.900
First, dial 2-1-1 from many phone.

14:42.400 --> 14:44.880
Here in Nevada County, that's 2-1-1 connecting point.

14:44.880 --> 14:49.600
It's free, confidential, answer 24-7 in English and Spanish.

14:50.000 --> 14:53.920
And a real person helps you find food, housing, healthcare, you name it.

14:54.300 --> 14:56.580
Second, go to findhelp.org.

14:57.120 --> 15:00.860
Type in your zip code and it shows you free and reduced cost programs near you.

15:01.520 --> 15:04.420
And third, visit us at techempower.org.

15:04.700 --> 15:06.480
And while you're there, click Join our Discord.

15:06.980 --> 15:08.380
It's our Discord server.

15:08.800 --> 15:10.520
That's our free online chat community.

15:11.220 --> 15:13.580
If you want one-on-one help, we answer.

15:14.420 --> 15:17.660
Next time on Wait I Qualify, getting connected.

15:18.180 --> 15:21.780
We're going to talk about free and low-cost internet, how to get a free phone plan,

15:21.900 --> 15:24.320
and how to get online without breaking the bank.

15:25.220 --> 15:28.200
Until then, go find out what you qualify for.

15:28.700 --> 15:29.660
You might be surprised.

